  "doc_id": "41890",
  "text": "Intracellular signal transduction in neurons and synapses is characterized by a high degree of crosstalk. A great variety of initial steps, such as activation of many different cell membrane receptors, leads to changes in a rather limited number of enzymes that generate second messengers (adenylyl cyclase, phospholipases) and a limited number of second messengers inside the cell (calcium, cyclic adenosinemonophosphate, cyclic guanosine monophosphate, inositol 1,4,5-triphosphate; reviewed in de Jong and Verhage [CITATION_1] ). Hence, it is plausible that genetic variation in the genes encoding these factors has similar biological consequences and additive contributions to pathogenesis.",
